#OUTLIER IMPUTATION using 3s rule

def outliers(feat):
 upper_limit = feat.mean() + 3*feat.std()#upper limit
 lower_limit = feat.mean() - 3*feat.std()#lower limit

 feat = np.where(
    feat >upper_limit,
    upper_limit,# feature having rows more than upper limit, set it to upper limit value
    np.where(
       feat <lower_limit,
        lower_limit,# feature having rows less than lower limit, set it to lower limit value
        feat ))
 return feat

#features to be normalized using minmax scaler
npt = MinMaxScaler()#Minmax scaler is used to scale the data.
npt.fit(df[["loan_amnt", "term", "annual_inc"]])#fitting the numerical columns

def get_npt(df):
    temp_df = pd.DataFrame(data=npt.transform(df[["loan_amnt", "term", "annual_inc"]]),columns=npt.get_feature_names_out(["loan_amnt", "term", "annual_inc"]))#transform and geting the feature names the numerical columns
    df.drop(columns=["loan_amnt", "term", "annual_inc"], axis=1, inplace=True)#drop the numerical columns which are tarnsformed in the previous step.
    df = pd.concat([df.reset_index(drop=True), temp_df], axis=1)#concat the new transformed columns
    return df

4.Modelling¶

In [30]:
#Defining an Evaluation Function to Run the Model

def evaluate(model,X_train,X_test,Y_train,Y_test):
    
    model.fit(X_train,Y_train)#Fit train and test data
    predictions_train = model.predict(X_train)#predict train data
    predictions_test = model.predict(X_test)#predict test data
    
    errors_train = abs(predictions_train - Y_train)#find error in train data
    errors_test = abs(predictions_test - Y_test)#find error in test data
    
    mape_train = 100 * np.mean(errors_train / Y_train)#calculate Mean Absolute percentage error(mape) for train data
    mape_test = 100 * np.mean(errors_test / Y_test)#calculate Mean Absolute percentage error(mape) for test data
    
    accuracy_train = 100 - mape_train#calculate accuracy of train data 
    accuracy_test = 100 - mape_test#calculate accuracy of test data 
    
    R_square = r2_score(Y_test,predictions_test)#calculate the r-square score
 
    # Print out the results
    print('Model Performance')
    print('R square score = {:0.2f}.'.format(R_square))
    print('Average Error(Train Data): {:0.4f} of int rate.'.format(np.mean(errors_train)))
    print('Average Error(Test Data): {:0.4f} of int rate.'.format(np.mean(errors_test)))
    
    print('Accuracy(Train Data) = {:0.2f}%.'.format(accuracy_train))
    print('Accuracy(Test Data) = {:0.2f}%.'.format(accuracy_test))
    
    print('Mean Absolute error (Train Data): {:0.4f} of int rate'.format(mape_train))
    print('Mean Absolute error(Test Data): {:0.4f} of int rate'.format(mape_test))
    
    # Plot the results for checking distribution of error(comparing train and test set)
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,10))
    plt.scatter(predictions_train,(predictions_train - Y_train),c='g',s=40,alpha=0.5)
    plt.scatter(predictions_test,(predictions_test - Y_test),c='b',s=40,alpha=0.5)
    plt.hlines(y=0,xmin=0,xmax=30)
    plt.title('residual plot blue(test) and green(train)data')
    plt.ylabel('residuals')
    return accuracy_train,accuracy_test

In [35]:
# Number of trees in random forest
n_estimators = [10,20,30,50,100]
# Number of features to consider at every split
max_features = ['auto', 'sqrt']
# Maximum number of levels in tree
max_depth = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(10, 110, num = 11)]
max_depth.append(None)
# Minimum number of samples required to split a node
min_samples_split = [2, 5, 10]
# Minimum number of samples required at each leaf node
min_samples_leaf = [1, 2, 4]
# Method of selecting samples for training each tree
bootstrap = [True, False]

# Create the grid

random_grid = {'n_estimators': n_estimators,
               'max_features': max_features,
               'max_depth': max_depth,
               'min_samples_split': min_samples_split,
               'min_samples_leaf': min_samples_leaf,
               'bootstrap': bootstrap}

# Use the random grid to search for best hyperparameters
# First create the base model to tune
rf = RandomForestRegressor(random_state = 42)

rf_random = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=rf, param_distributions=random_grid,
                              n_iter = 10, scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error', 
                              cv = 5, verbose=2, random_state=42, n_jobs=-1,
                              return_train_score=True)

# Fit the random search model
rf_random.fit(train_features, train_labels);
